node.text: Short film by @taylorglenn | We all know people whose dedication to a passion or purpose inspires us deeply. Gannett Horn's (@surfasaur) focus on his sport and love for its community embodies the best in each of us. This short film is a testament to Gannett and those who motivate us to work harder at the things we love. #riversurfing Production by @apresvisuals

node.text: Time-lapse by @mikeolbinski / Watching this tornado form right in front our eyes on May 16, 2021, near Sudan, Texas, was incredible. It dropped harmlessly in a field, nowhere near structures or people, and lasted only 5-10 minutes. As a guy who strives for amazing time-lapse footage of storms, this was one of the highlights of the year!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on August 31, 2021. May be an image of nature and body of water.

node.text: Photo by @erinhogue / Beauty at the end of the rainbow. This photo is from a trip where nothing went according to plan. I arrived in Australia to document a 3-month journey that unexpectedly ended as soon as I got there. Being unbelievably stubborn at times, I refused to let unfortunate circumstances put an end to my first big photo assignment. With the help of a handful of amazing friends, an unbelievably supportive editor, and one particularly welcoming family, I still had a successful trip. I was able to stay in Australia, produce wonderful stories, and have the trip of a lifetime.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Adventure on August 31, 2021. May be an image of nature and ocean.

node.text: Photos by @praveenjayakaran / I have been shooting the surfing championship in India every year since 2016. I missed it big-time last year due to COVID-19 lockdown, but we fortunately have the competition back once again. Yay! I went to the competition and was there for two entire days to document the sport, and I witnessed kids who were killing it. I must say it was super fun to be there and see them all. Here is some of the action to feast your eyes on. :) #surfing #swell #extremesports #adventureislife #surfingchampionship

node.text: Photo by @mikeolbinski / Sometimes you chase storms all day without much hope for anything awesome, but then you find yourself on a storm near Andrews, Texas, only to watch microburst after microburst drop from the same storm and create one of the most incredible scenes I've ever personally witnessed. We just stood there in awe at what unfolded before our eyes ... not to mention the blues and sunset pinks/reds backlighting the storm. We knew people would likely not believe the colors were real, but they were!

node.text: Photo by @ming.t.poon / Andrew McLean (@straightchuter) dropping into one of the many bowls of Gulmarg Kashmir, Pir Panjal Range of the Himalaya. You can see Andrew ski cut the slope before committing to the bowl and the enormous avalanche path. Gulmarg has amazing bowls for skiing and riding, but the terrain creates some of the biggest avalanche paths I've experienced. Many are miles long and have more than 4,000 feet (1,200 meters) of vertical relief. While always cautious and continually assessing, we were constantly thanking the stars for the uncharacteristically stable snowpack we experienced on our trip. If traveling to Gulmarg for skiing or riding, I recommend hiring a local, internationally accredited guide. Looking forward to returning to the slopes and warm people of Kashmir.
